  "prompt": "Can a private company take loan from another private company as per provision of Companies Act 2013?",
  "response": "Yes, a private company can take a loan from another private company as per the provisions of the **Companies Act, 2013**, provided certain conditions and limitations are met. Here are the key aspects to consider:\n\n### 1. **Limitations on Borrowing Powers**\n   - A company can borrow money only if it is authorized by its **Memorandum of Association (MOA)** and **Articles of Association (AOA)**.\n   - The borrowing must be within the **borrowing limits** prescribed by the Act and as specified in the company's MOA/AOA.\n\n### 2. **Inter-Corporate Loans**\n   - **Section 185** of the Act restricts loans to directors or their relatives, but it does not prohibit loans between private companies.\n   - **Section 186** of the Act regulates inter-corporate loans and investments. A company can lend or give a loan to another company, provided:\n     - The total amount of loans, investments, guarantees, and security provided by the lending company does not exceed **60% of its paid-up share capital, free reserves, and securities premium** (or **100%** if shareholder approval is obtained).\n     - The loan must comply with the conditions specified under Section 186.\n\n### 3. **Approval Requirements**\n   - If the loan exceeds the prescribed limits under Section 186, **prior approval of the shareholders** by way of a **special resolution** is required.\n   - The loan agreement must be properly documented, and the terms and conditions should be disclosed to the shareholders.\n\n### 4. **Interest on Loans**\n   - The loan may be interest-bearing or interest-free, but it should be at arm\u2019s length and not violate any tax or regulatory provisions.\n\n### 5. **Related Party Transactions**\n   - If the loan is given to a **related party**, it must comply with the provisions of **Section 188** of the Act. Prior approval of the **Board of Directors** and **shareholders** (in certain cases) is required.\n\n### 6. **Compliance with RBI Regulations**\n   - If the loan involves foreign exchange or foreign companies, **Reserve Bank of India (RBI)** regulations must also be adhered to.\n\n### 7. **Record Keeping**\n   - Proper records of the loan transaction must be maintained, and it should be disclosed in the company\u2019s financial statements.\n\n### Conclusion\nA private company can take a loan from another private company under the Companies Act, 2013, subject to compliance with the borrowing limits, approval requirements, and other conditions specified in the Act. It is advisable to consult a legal or financial advisor to ensure full compliance with all applicable laws.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
